## Step 8: Make It Continuous Purple Teaming, Not One‑Off Battles

The most effective orgs treat AI red vs blue as an ongoing collaboration, not a yearly event. [web:253][web:256][web:271][web:284]

Good patterns:

- Joint planning:
  - Red, blue, AI/ML, and product agree on objectives, scope, and success criteria for each exercise. [web:259][web:271][web:284]
- Regular exercises:
  - Schedule AI‑focused purple‑team runs (e.g. quarterly) around your highest‑risk AI systems and workflows. [web:253][web:271][web:284]
- Shared knowledge base:
  - Store attack prompts, behaviours, detections, fixes, and lessons learned in one place (internal wiki or dedicated AI security repo). [web:259][web:280]
- Feedback into standards:
  - Align your defences with emerging secure‑AI frameworks and guidance as they evolve. [web:272][web:275][web:277]

The goal is not to “win” against your AI red team, but to use it as a continuous pressure test that helps your AI‑augmented blue team learn, adapt, and harden systems faster than real attackers can.

---

If you treat AI red teaming as a sparring partner and build the right blue‑team muscles around it — data controls, guardrails, monitoring, automation, and tight feedback loops — you’ll end up with AI systems that are not just clever, but resilient.

